 seems like the behavior hinges on how ClassLoader.loadClass handles calls — should we wrap the import in this process too? If unsupported errors occur, I wonder about using a helper function to manage exceptions. I want to make sure we remain within test parameters for native images. We need to navigate these subtleties carefully to ensure effective functionality.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading assertions**\\n\\nI’m thinking about using `val loaded = loadClassAllowing...` and checking if it's not null before making an assertion. But I'm wondering whether a conditional assert might come off as a bit \\\"skip-ish\\\"? It seems allowable if we're working with unsupported dynamic class loading since resource calls still run. But do we actually need that? I’m not sure it’s necessary. Existing tests might already be handling class loading in a similar way, so I’m weighing my options here.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_my9N1K6CXtP4AnGMJthEAq2S|fc_0ad52cba65e839250169fa2517a0a0819c82217aa590a2cb18", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.jetbrains.kotlin/kotlin-main-kts/2.3.21/src/test/kotlin/org_jetbrains_kotlin/kotlin_main_kts/ClassRealmTest.kt", "offset": 1, "limit": 200}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2902, "output": 847, "cacheRead": 43520, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 47269, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778001163406, "responseId": "resp_0ad52cba65e839250169fa250c2810819c85c612eb9b33a508"}}
